Day 11 - CSS

Table:

 <thead> - table head
 <tr> - table row
 <th> - table header
 <tbody> - table body
 <td> - table data

 Example:
 <!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Day 10 | Learn HTML, CSS</title>
</head>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
<body>
    <table>
        <thead> 
            <tr>
                <th>S.No</th>
                <th>Name</th>
                <th>Batch</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>Joe</td>
            <td>B54</td>
        </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>2</td>
            <td>John</td>
            <td>B53</td>
        </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>3</td>
            <td>Doe</td>
            <td>B52</td>
        </tr>
            <tr>
            <td>4</td>
            <td>Js</td>
            <td>B51</td>
        </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
</body>
</html>

pseudo class: hover, active, visited, link

--mouse over
a:hover{
    text-decoration: underline;
}

--clicked
a:active{
    color: aqua;
}

--visited
a:visited{
    color: brown;
}

--unvisited
a:link{
    color: brown;
}

Overflow:
1. Visible
2. Hidden
3. Scroll
4. Auto

Example:
.main{
    border: 1px solid black;
    padding: 12px;
    height: 200px;
    overflow: auto;
}

Task: Bio Data, h:100px, scroll
Task: Using table Time table.

* Gradients: it helps us to have the transition linear and radical gradient.
            linear gradient will have default flow of top to bottom.
            radical gradient will have the circle inside the box.

Syntax: background-image: linear-gradient(direction/angle, starting color....ending color);
                                          to right/120

Example: background-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, red 70%, rgb(249, 225, 229) 30%);
